RNA-seq HOMEWORK

Aleksandra Kurowska

January 27, 2024

Dataset: GSE195727 Purpose: Identify differences in gene expression profiles in fetal monocytes - cells that persist and differentiate postnatally - according to distinct placental histologic domains. Methods: We first isolated classical and intermediate monocyte subsets via FACS and performed transcriptomic profiling of 140 samples (70 classical (cMNC) and 70 intermediate monocyte (iMNC) samples) using bulk RNA-Seq.

PCA

Principal component analysis shows a distinct speration of two cell types. We can see first component explaning 22% of vairance and spliting the cells in two clusters.

Quality Control with NOISeq

Before analysing the dataset, the first step was to perfom a quality tests of the samples.

Biotype detection

Above figure shows the relative abundance of biotypes in the two samples compared. In RNA-seq, it is expected that most of the genes will be protein-coding so detecting an enrichment in the sample of any other biotype could point to a potential contamination or at least provide information on the sample composition to take decision on the type of analysis to be performed.

Counts per million

Features with low counts are, in general, less reliable and may introduce noise in the data. The above figure helps to decide the threshold to remove low-count features by indicating the proportion of such features that are present in our data.

Differential Expression

I have performed differential expression analysis in DESeq using Wald test. For filtering significantly de-regulated genes I have used the following thresholds: adjusted p.value < 0.05 and |log2FoldChange| > 1. In total we were able to detect 522 differentially expressed genes, 357 down-regulated and 195 up-regulated between intermediate monocytes and classical monocytes.

The above heatmap shows top 50 differentially expressed genes.

Functional Enrichment

The above figure represents enriched pathways for up-regulated genes after applying the hypergeometric test. Based on the literature, monocyte subsets, including classical, intermediate, and non-classical monocytes, demonstrate distinct functional properties, which are influenced by their gene expression and methylation status. Intermediate monocytes exhibit high levels of antigen presentation-related molecules and secrete various cytokines. Their role in immunity is complex and still being elucidated, as they are known to produce both pro- and anti-inflammatory mediators. With the agreement of the current knowledge, our analysis shows the most significant pathways that are related with the immune response as well as mediated immuny of leukocytes or lymphocytes. Additionally, I have also identified significant enrichment for leukocyte activation based on Gene Ontology GO:0002252, which was reported in the paper.

Conclusions

Transcriptomic profiling of cord blood monocyte subsets identifies cell type–specific changes associated with different domains of placental pathology.
